> This guide only scratches the surface of the powerful, expressive language that is JavaScript. 
The following are some of the best resources on the web if you want to take your learning 
further.

## Getting started

* [JavaScript Guide](https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Guide) -- Mozilla Developer 
  Center

## References

* [JavaScript Reference](https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Reference) -- Mozilla Developer 
  Center

## Tools

* [JavaScript console](http://jsconsole.com) -- by [Remy Sharp](http://twitter.com/rem)
* [JSLint](http://jslint.com) -- by Douglas Crockford, Yahoo!'s Chief JavaScript Architect

## Advanced topics

* [ECMA-262](http://dmitrysoshnikov.com/ecmascript/) -- deep exploration of the language, by 
  JavaScript theoretician, [Dmitry Soshnikov](http://twitter.com/DmitrySoshnikov)

## Blogs & people

* [DailyJS](http://dailyjs.com/)
* [Douglas Crockford's JavaScript](http://javascript.crockford.com/) -- by the Yahoo! JavaScript 
  architect of the same name

## Books (yes, they still print books)

* [JavaScript, The Good Parts](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0596517742/practjavas-20) -- by 
  Douglas Crockford
* [JavaScript Patterns](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0596806752/practjavas-20) -- by 
  Stoyan Stefanov
* [JavaScript: The Definitive Guide](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0596101996/practjavas-20) -- 
  by David Flanagan (look for a quote from me on the back cover of the 4th edition!)

